<article>
    <h1>Re&#xAD;cent lapses in pub&#xAD;lic health&#xAD;care sys&#xAD;tem</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201212/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-12"><time>2020-12-12</time></a>
        - <span>THE BIG STORY</span>
        - <span role="byline">Prisca Ang</span>
    </section>

    <p>HEP­ATI­TIS C VIRUS OUT­BREAK</p>
    <p>Lapses at Sin­ga­pore Gen­eral Hos­pi­tal in 2015 led to a ma­jor out­break of hep­ati­tis C that in­fected 25 peo­ple, eight of whom died.</p>
    <p>An in­de­pen­dent re­view com­mit­tee pointed to short­com­ings at the hos­pi­tal and gaps in the Ministry of Health’s in­fec­tious dis­eases re­port­ing sys­tem.</p>
    <p>SINGHEALTH CY­BER AT­TACK</p>
    <p>Hack­ers stole the per­sonal par­tic­u­lars of 1.5 mil­lion pa­tients in Sin­ga­pore’s worst cy­ber at­tack.</p>
    <p>Around 160,000 of the pa­tients, in­clud­ing Prime Min­is­ter Lee Hsien Loong and a few min­is­ters, had their out­pa­tient pre­scrip­tions stolen as well.</p>
    <p>The hack­ers had in­fil­trated the com­put­ers of SingHealth, Sin­ga­pore’s largest pub­lic health­care clus­ter, be­tween June 27 and July 4, 2018.</p>
    <p>EQUIP­MENT NOT STERILISED PROP­ERLY AT DENTAL CLINIC</p>
    <p>A dental clinic at Tan Tock Seng Hos­pi­tal used eight packs of equip­ment that had not been com­pletely sterilised on some pa­tients.</p>
    <p>Eigh­teen staff faced dis­ci­plinary ac­tion, in­clud­ing fi­nan­cial penal­ties and warn­ings, over the lapses be­tween Nov 28 and Dec 5, 2018.</p>
    <p>The hos­pi­tal said the pa­tients’ risk of in­fec­tion was ex­tremely low as the in­stru­ments had un­der­gone two rounds of ster­il­i­sa­tion. The equip­ment had, how­ever, missed the fi­nal round of steam ster­il­i­sa­tion to re­move bac­te­rial spores.</p>


